---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>Two models. Two paradigms. Both autonomously proved <code>∀ n m : Nat, n + m = m + n</code>
in Lean 4 — no human in the loop, no cloud APIs. One was a strategist; the other, a speedrunner.
Here's how we got there.</p>

<h2>The Results</h2>

<p><strong>Strategist — DeepSeek-R1:8B</strong> (77.1s, 1 attempt)</p>

<pre><code>theorem nat_add_comm (n m : Nat) : n + m = m + n := by
  omega</code></pre>

<p>R1 thinks for ~75 seconds in a single long chain-of-thought, reasoning about induction vs.
automation, then emits clean JSON with <code>omega</code> at 0.95 confidence. One shot, done.</p>

<p><strong>Speedrunner — DeepSeek-Prover-V2:7B Q8_0</strong> (32.7s, 7 iterations)</p>

<pre><code>theorem nat_add_comm (n m : Nat) : n + m = m + n := by
  all_goals omega</code></pre>

<p>Prover-V2 fires ~1.5 seconds per iteration, outputting raw Lean tactics instead of JSON.
It took 7 iterations to land on <code>all_goals omega</code>, but at 32.7s total it was still
2.4× faster than R1.</p>

<h2>Model Comparison</h2>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Metric</th><th>deepseek-r1:8b</th><th>deepseek-prover-v2:7b-q8</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Total time</td><td>77.1s</td><td>32.7s</td></tr>
<tr><td>Per-iteration</td><td>~75s</td><td>~1–2s</td></tr>
<tr><td>Iterations</td><td>1</td><td>7</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tactic found</td><td><code>omega</code></td><td><code>all_goals omega</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Output format</td><td>Clean JSON</td><td>Prose + Lean (auto-wrapped)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Size</td><td>5.2 GB</td><td>6.8 GB</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h2>The Quantization Trap</h2>

<p>We nearly shipped a broken model. When we first pulled Prover-V2, we tried Q4_K_M to save
VRAM. It caused significant execution errors:</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Quant</th><th>Size</th><th>Output Quality</th><th>Speed</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Q4_K_M</td><td>3.9 GB</td><td>🚫 Emoji prose (🎉👨‍✈️⚡ LEAN_PROOF!)</td><td>700ms</td></tr>
<tr><td>Q8_0</td><td>6.8 GB</td><td>✅ Clean Lean tactics</td><td>1.8s</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Q4_K_M degraded the weights responsible for Lean 4 syntax and structured output. The model
would hallucinate emoji-laden prose instead of valid tactics. Q8_0 preserved the critical
weights — the 2.9 GB overhead is non-negotiable for this use case.</p>

<h2>The Architecture</h2>

<p>Perqed's proof loop is a generator-discriminator:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Z3 pre-flight:</strong> Before proving anything, Z3 hunts for counterexamples in bounded
  domains. If the theorem is false, we find out in 50ms.</li>
  <li><strong>LLM generation:</strong> The formalist agent reads the current Lean tactic state and proposes
  tactics — via structured JSON (R1) or raw tactic output (Prover-V2).</li>
  <li><strong>Bare-tactic wrapping:</strong> Prover-V2's raw output passes through <code>sanitizeR1Output()</code>,
  which strips thinking blocks, extracts Lean tactics, and wraps them into our
  <code>FormalistResponse</code> schema.</li>
  <li><strong>Lean verification:</strong> Each proposed tactic is piped to <code>lean --stdin --run</code>.
  Lean is the sole arbiter of truth.</li>
  <li><strong>Parallel speculation:</strong> All tactics run concurrently. First complete proof wins.</li>
</ol>

<h2>The Debugging Journey</h2>

<h3>The <code>num_predict</code> Trap (R1)</h3>

<p>DeepSeek-R1 uses extended <code>&lt;think&gt;...&lt;/think&gt;</code> reasoning chains that can run 2,000+ tokens
before producing the final JSON answer. Ollama's default <code>num_predict</code> of 128 cuts this off
mid-thought, producing truncated garbage.</p>

<p>The fix: set <code>num_predict: 4096</code>. This gives the model enough runway to complete its
full chain-of-thought <em>and</em> the final structured output.</p>

<h3>The Think-Tag Parser (R1)</h3>

<p>R1's output wraps reasoning in XML-like <code>&lt;think&gt;</code> tags before the JSON payload.
Our FormalistAgent needed a custom parser that strips the thinking block, extracts the JSON,
validates against our Zod schema, and falls back to regex extraction if <code>JSON.parse</code> fails.</p>

<h3>Bare-Tactic Wrapping (Prover-V2)</h3>

<p>Prover-V2 doesn't speak JSON — it outputs raw Lean tactics, sometimes wrapped in markdown
fences, sometimes preceded by thinking prose. We built <code>sanitizeR1Output()</code> to handle all
variants: single tactics, multi-line blocks, <code>lean</code>-fenced code, and empty thinking tags.</p>

<h2>Test Results</h2>

<p><strong>108/108 GREEN</strong> across 12 files, 209 assertions, 0 regressions.</p>

<ul>
  <li>4 new bare-tactic wrapping tests (single, multi-line, lean-fence, empty thinking)</li>
  <li>All Sprint 1–6 tests pass unchanged</li>
</ul>

<h2>What This Means</h2>

<p>We now have two viable proving paradigms on commodity hardware:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>R1 (strategist)</strong> — one long think, high-confidence JSON output, ideal when you want
  a single high-quality attempt</li>
  <li><strong>Prover-V2 (speedrunner)</strong> — fast iterations, raw tactic output, 2.4× faster
  wall-clock for this theorem</li>
</ul>

<p>The architecture handles both seamlessly. The bare-tactic wrapper unifies their output
into the same <code>FormalistResponse</code> schema, so the orchestrator doesn't care which model
is upstream.</p>

<h2>Cost Analysis</h2>

<p>The local models (R1, Prover-V2) are free. The only cloud cost comes from the Architect —
Gemini 3.0 Flash (preview) for planning and 3.1 Pro (preview) for hard escalations.
Most proof runs are Flash-dominant, with Pro only firing on repeated failures.</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Tier</th><th>Input (20K tokens)</th><th>Output (2.5K tokens)</th><th>Total / proof run</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>3.1 Pro</td><td>$0.025</td><td>$0.025</td><td>$0.05</td></tr>
<tr><td>3.0 Flash</td><td>$0.01</td><td>$0.0075</td><td>~$0.02</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Blended</strong></td><td></td><td></td><td><strong>~$0.03</strong></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>At ~$0.03 per proof, that's roughly <strong>33 proofs per dollar</strong>. Cheap, but a real number
worth tracking — not a rounding error.</p>

<p>Next up: harder theorems. We're targeting Mathlib lemmas, starting with basic algebra
and working toward real analysis.</p>

<hr>

<p><em>Perqed is open source. <a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed">Follow us on GitHub</a>
or <a href="/minutiae/">watch the agent think in real time</a>.</em></p>
`;
